2026-07-16  learn: done. reference/ats-sequence-of-operation.md.
            The domain thesis, and it is 03's version of 01 refusing to print a tier, reached from a
            completely different direction: THERE IS NO "THE" ATS SEQUENCE. ASCO and Russelectric agree
            on structure completely and disagree on numbers by 6x (retransfer 30 min vs 300 sec) and
            3x (momentary override 1 sec vs 3 sec). Neither is wrong. So the sim names its vendor on
            every screen. Two independent projects arriving at the same refusal is what makes it a rule
            rather than a quirk of one document.
            Wrote up why each timer exists rather than what each timer is, because the reason is what
            makes it memorable: 1C is the switch declining to panic over a recloser operation, 3A is
            the switch refusing to believe a utility that just failed and is probably still being
            worked on, 2E is entirely for the engine and not for the load. Read in order, the sequence
            is one argument about what deserves to be believed.
            Recorded the trap that nearly got me: IN PHASE MONITOR IS NOT SYNC CHECK. Different
            features, different switch models (ASCO's own table marks in sync 7ACTS/7ACTB only, in
            phase monitor 7ATS/7ATB), and only the closed transition's sync check has the 5 degree
            window. Carrying 5 degrees across to the open transition monitor because both features say
            "phase" would be inventing a spec and citing ASCO for it.
            Also documented the four refusals the build inherits: no vendor neutral defaults, no
            extended parallel control, surface the Shed Load contradiction rather than resolve it, no
            NFPA 110 verbatim.

2026-07-16  build: done. build/vendors.js + engine.js + index.html.
            Zero dependencies, no CDN, no build step. Hand rolled SVG, same as 01 and 02.
            The engine is a deterministic event simulator: named vendor profile + scenario in, an
            ordered timeline of events out, each event carrying the manual page it comes from. It
            has NO VENDOR NEUTRAL MODE and throws without a profile, which is the whole thesis
            expressed as a type error rather than a paragraph.
            THREE THINGS THE ENGINE DOES NOT KNOW AND SAYS SO, rather than guessing: how long two
            live sources sit paralleled (emitted as duration: null), what a switch does after the
            failure to synchronize timer expires (terminal, marked unsourced), and the physical
            contact transfer time of an open transition (modelled instantaneous, labelled). Each is
            asserted in verify/ so a later session cannot quietly fill one in.
            Chart is a LOG TIME AXIS, log10(t+1), and the note under it says so in those words. The
            sequence spans 1 second (the 1C override) to 2160 seconds (30 min retransfer + 5 min
            cooldown). On a linear axis every decision the switch makes collapses into the first half
            percent of the width. Log keeps t=0 at the origin and keeps the ORDER honest, which is
            what a sequence of operation is about. Spacing is a ratio, never a duration.
            Russelectric ships as a two row divergence TABLE, not a second simulator. Only two of its
            timers were traced; inventing the other ten from ASCO's shape would fabricate exactly the
            vendor agreement this project exists to disprove. `runnable: false`, and the engine says
            why when you try.

2026-07-16  verify: done. 63 checks, 0 failures. node verify/verify.js
            29 mutants, all dead. ./tools/gate.sh green across the whole repo.
            A THIRD SHAPE OF VERIFY, and worth naming: 01 checked a structural claim against a prose
            verdict, 02 checked arithmetic against a 210 cell table. An ATS sequence is a STATE
            MACHINE and ASCO publishes no filled in timeline to diff against. So this suite asserts
            that published numbers appear at published times, that the one published numeric
            criterion is reproduced AT ITS BOUNDARY, that published ranges are enforced, and that the
            deadband behaves as two thresholds require.
            THE BOUNDARY IS THE POINT: ASCO says "must be LESS THAN 5 degrees", so exactly 5.0 is NOT
            in sync, and the suite asserts that on all three criteria. Reproducing a published
            criterion and approximating it are different things and only the boundary tells them
            apart.
            SECTION F IS THE PRODUCT: twelve checks that assert what the tool REFUSES to claim. An
            absence is not self enforcing. Nothing stopped a future session from finding Rev K's 0.5
            sec extended parallel default, thinking "the manual publishes it", and adding the slider,
            so there is now a check that greps the whole build for that number and for XtdParallelTD.
            Four mutants exist purely to prove those refusals are load bearing: they break no
            calculation at all, they just make the tool CLAIM MORE THAN ITS SOURCE. All four die.
            🔴 A MUTANT DELIBERATELY NOT WRITTEN, and the reasoning is the useful part: loosening the
            1C comparison from < to <= changes only what happens at an outage of EXACTLY 1.000 s, and
            ASCO does not publish what the switch does at that instant. The sync criterion's boundary
            IS published, so it is asserted and mutated. This one is not. Adding the mutant would
            have forced an assertion about UNSOURCED behaviour in order to kill it, which is how a
            suite starts inventing facts to keep itself green. One boundary is in the book. The other
            is not. Only mutate the one that is.
            ⚠ RUNNER CONSTRAINT FOUND HERE: mutants.txt is parsed with `IFS='|' read`, so a sed
            expression MAY NOT CONTAIN A PIPE. `s/a && b/a || b/` truncates silently at the first
            pipe. Expressed "any one criterion suffices" by dropping each criterion in turn instead,
            which is a better test anyway: it proves each is individually load bearing.
            TWO BUGS FOUND BY DRIVING THE REAL PAGE, neither visible to the node suite:
            1. STRUCTURAL: the "Emergency source" lane label rendered at x = -13, outside the
               viewBox, silently clipped, because the left margin was 92px and the label is 97px. A
               clipped label still looks like a label, so a screenshot could not see it. Fixed, and
               PROMOTED TO A PERMANENT CHECK (verify section G2) against the measured width.
            2. VISUAL, and only a human eye catches this one: the emergency source lane read
               "failed" at t=0. It has not failed. The generator is not running yet. One state name
               ('dead') meant two different things on two different lanes, and the word described a
               healthy standby plant as a fault. Now per lane: "not running" vs "failed".
               This is why the visual pass happens even when the structural check is clean.
